:Ligue 1 players]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Eastern name order|Nagy Antal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antal Nagy\n| image = Nagy Antal 2011.jpg\n| fullname = Antal Nagy\n| height = 1.87 m\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|10|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Nagyhal\u00e1sz]], Hungary\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1975\u20131976  | years2 = 1976\u20131986  | years3 = 1986\u20131987  | years4 = 1987\u20131990\n| clubs1 = [[Szegedi EOL]]  | clubs2 = [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Budapest Honved]]  | clubs3 = [[AS Nancy|Nancy]]  | clubs4 = [[Yverdon-Sport FC]]\n| caps1 = 14| goals1 = 2| caps2 = 279| goals2 = 40| caps3 = 37 | goals3 = 4| caps4 = | goals4 = \n| nationalyears1= 1979\u20131988\n| nationalteam1= [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]]\n| nationalcaps1= 32 | nationalgoals1 = 5\n}}\n\n'''Antal Nagy''' (born 17 October 1956) is a former Hungarian [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref>http://www.asnl.net/pages/club/joueurs/n.html</ref><ref>http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/hong-recintlp.html</ref><ref>http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupc_sov_v_hun.html</ref><ref>{{FootballDatabase.eu|46011<!-- -antal-nagy -->}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hungary Squad 1986 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nagy, Antal}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Hungarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Hungary international footballers]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC players]]\n[[Category:AS Nancy players]]\n[[Category:Yverdon Sport FC players]]\n[[Category:Hungarian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n\n\n{{Hungary-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "correct link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antal_Nagy_(footballer,_born_1956)"}
{"title_page": "Colchester Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name                  = Colchester Hospital\n| org/group             = [[East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| logo                  = \n| logo_size             = \n| image                 = File:Colchester General Hospital main entrance.jpg\n| image_size            =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Main entrance\n| coordinates           ={{coord|51.9099|0.8992|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| map_type              =Essex\n| map_caption           =Shown in Essex\n| location              = [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], England, United Kingdom\n| region                = \n| state                 = \n| country               = \n| healthcare            = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| funding               = \n| type                  = General\n| religious_affiliation = \n| affiliation           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n* [[Norwich Medical School]]\n}}\n| patron                = \n| network               = \n| standards             = \n| emergency             = Yes\n| beds                  = 763\n| speciality            = \n| helipad               = Yes\n| h1-number             = \n| h1-length-f           = \n| h1-length-m           = \n| h1-surface            = <!-- up to h12 -->\n| founded               = 1985\n| closed                = \n| demolished            = \n| website               = {{URL|https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/}}\n| other_links           = \n| module                = \n}}\n\n'''Colchester Hospital''' is a district general hospital located in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]]. It is managed by [[East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, then named Colchester District General Hospital, was opened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] on 17 May 1985, at a cost of \u00a316 million. At the time, it had nine wards and 283 beds, built in groups around landscaped courtyards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/mainstream/mainstreammay15.pdf|format=PDF|title=Mainstream|website=Colchesterhospital.nhs.uk|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol9/pp284-290|title=Hospitals {{!}} British History Online|website=British-history.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital has been expanded a number of times since its opening, and several new buildings have been added. This includes the Gainsborough wing, which opened in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|author=Will Lodge |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/colchester-hospital-s-2m-breast-unit-plans-revealed-1-4993630 |title=Colchester hospital\u2019s \u00a32m breast unit plans revealed &#124; Latest Suffolk and Essex News - East Anglian Daily Times |publisher=Eadt.co.uk |date=27 April 2017|accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust|trust]] announced that the nearby Essex County Hospital was due to close, and that some services currently provided there would transfer to Colchester General Hospital, including breast services and nuclear medicine. In preparation for this, construction began on a new diagnostic imaging centre, which opened in 2018, in time for the transfer of services. It houses three [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] scanners, one of which is wide bore, as well a [[PET-CT]] scanner, which will also be used by patients from the [[Ipswich]] and [[Chelmsford]] areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/essexcountytransfer.shtml|title=Colchester Hospital University - Essex County Transfer of Services|website=Colchesterhospital.nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/work-to-begin-on-diagnostic-centre-at-colchester-general-hospital-this-week-1-4876883|title=Work to begin on diagnostic centre at Colchester General Hospital this week|last=Lodge|first=Will|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=24 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, plans were approved to rebuild and extend the main entrance of the hospital. The Accident & Emergency department will also be expanded, and the narrow bridge across the lake in front of the hospital will also be replaced with a wider structure.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nick Hume on his role at Colchester Hospital|url=https://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/17497142.nick-hume-on-his-role-at-colchester-hospital/ |publisher=Daily Gazette|date=17 March 2019 |accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe hospital has a helipad, used by air ambulances and for military training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://associationofairambulances.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Helipads-Report-Dec-2014-Final-Web.pdf|format=PDF|title=Rotor Aircraft Landing Facilities : Light / Medium Aircraft Report|website=Associationofairambulances.co.uk|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Teaching ==\nThe hospital serves as a teaching hospital for medical students from [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]] and [[Norwich Medical School]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Key Facts - Medicine MBBS 5 Years (A100) - Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/smd/undergraduate/courses/a100/ |website=Queen Mary University of London |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Norwich Medical School |url=https://www.jpaget.nhs.uk/education-research/norwich-medical-school/ |website=James Paget University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nLocal bus routes 8, 84 and 84B, operated by [[Arriva UK Bus|Arriva]], and 61, 65 and 68, operated by [[First Essex|First]], serve the hospital, with a bus stop located outside the main entrance. There is also a Park and Ride service, run by [[Essex County Council]].<ref name=\"esneft1\">{{cite web|author=East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust |url=https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/your-visit/getting-here/how-to-get-to-colchester-hospital/ |title=Get to Colchester Hospital &#124; East Suffolk & North Essex NHS Foundation Trust |publisher=Esneft.nhs.uk |date=2018-07-01 |accessdate=2018-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essexhighways.org/Transport-and-Roads/Getting-Around/Bus/Park-and-Ride/Colchester-Park-and-Ride.aspx |title=Colchester Park and Ride &#124; Essex County Council |publisher=Essexhighways.org |date=31 July 2018|accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest railway station is [[Colchester railway station|Colchester]] on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]], located 1.6 miles from the hospital.<ref name=\"esneft1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/ Trust website]\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/Services/hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=13 Colchester Hospital on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.cqc.org.uk/location/RDEE4 Care Quality Commission inspection reports]\n{{Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Colchester (town)]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Essex]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name                  = Colchester Hospital\n| org/group             = [[East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| logo                  = \n| logo_size             = \n| image                 = File:Colchester General Hospital main entrance.jpg\n| image_size            =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Main entrance\n| coordinates           ={{coord|51.9099|0.8992|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| map_type              =Essex\n| map_caption           =Shown in Essex\n| location              = [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], England, United Kingdom\n| region                = \n| state                 = \n| country               = \n| healthcare            = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| funding               = \n| type                  = General\n| religious_affiliation = \n| affiliation           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n* [[Norwich Medical School]]\n}}\n| patron                = \n| network               = \n| standards             = \n| emergency             = Yes\n| beds                  = 763\n| speciality            = \n| helipad               = Yes\n| h1-number             = \n| h1-length-f           = \n| h1-length-m           = \n| h1-surface            = <!-- up to h12 -->\n| founded               = 1985\n| closed                = \n| demolished            = \n| website               = {{URL|https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/}}\n| other_links           = \n| module                = \n}}\n\n'''Colchester Hospital''' is a district general hospital located in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]]. It is managed by [[East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, then named Colchester District General Hospital, was opened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] on 17 May 1985, at a cost of \u00a316 million. At the time, it had nine wards and 283 beds, built in groups around landscaped courtyards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/mainstream/mainstreammay15.pdf|format=PDF|title=Mainstream|website=Colchesterhospital.nhs.uk|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol9/pp284-290|title=Hospitals {{!}} British History Online|website=British-history.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital has been expanded a number of times since its opening, and several new buildings have been added. This includes the Gainsborough wing, which opened in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|author=Will Lodge |url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/colchester-hospital-s-2m-breast-unit-plans-revealed-1-4993630 |title=Colchester hospital\u2019s \u00a32m breast unit plans revealed &#124; Latest Suffolk and Essex News - East Anglian Daily Times |publisher=Eadt.co.uk |date=27 April 2017|accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the [[Colchester Hospital University NHS Foundation Trust|trust]] announced that the nearby Essex County Hospital was due to close, and that some services currently provided there would transfer to Colchester General Hospital, including breast services and nuclear medicine. In preparation for this, construction began on a new diagnostic imaging centre, which opened in 2018, in time for the transfer of services. It houses three [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] scanners, one of which is wide bore, as well a [[PET-CT]] scanner, which will also be used by patients from the [[Ipswich]] and [[Chelmsford]] areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/essexcountytransfer.shtml|title=Colchester Hospital University - Essex County Transfer of Services|website=Colchesterhospital.nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/work-to-begin-on-diagnostic-centre-at-colchester-general-hospital-this-week-1-4876883|title=Work to begin on diagnostic centre at Colchester General Hospital this week|last=Lodge|first=Will|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=24 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, plans were approved to rebuild and extend the main entrance of the hospital. The Accident & Emergency department will also be expanded, and the narrow bridge across the lake in front of the hospital will also be replaced with a wider structure.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nick Hume on his role at Colchester Hospital|url=https://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/17497142.nick-hume-on-his-role-at-colchester-hospital/ |publisher=Daily Gazette|date=17 March 2019 |accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe hospital has a helipad, used by air ambulances and for military training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://associationofairambulances.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Helipads-Report-Dec-2014-Final-Web.pdf|format=PDF|title=Rotor Aircraft Landing Facilities : Light / Medium Aircraft Report|website=Associationofairambulances.co.uk|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Teaching ==\nThe hospital serves as a teaching hospital for medical students from [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]] and [[Norwich Medical School]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Key Facts - Medicine MBBS 5 Years (A100) - Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry |url=https://www.qmul.ac.uk/smd/undergraduate/courses/a100/ |website=Queen Mary University of London |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Norwich Medical School |url=https://www.jpaget.nhs.uk/education-research/norwich-medical-school/ |website=James Paget University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nLocal bus routes 8, 84 and 84B, operated by [[Arriva UK Bus|Arriva]], and 61, 65 and 68, operated by [[First Essex|First]], serve the hospital, with a bus stop located outside the main entrance. There is also a Park and Ride service, run by [[Essex County Council]].<ref name=\"esneft1\">{{cite web|author=East Suffolk and North Essex NHS Foundation Trust |url=https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/your-visit/getting-here/how-to-get-to-colchester-hospital/ |title=Get to Colchester Hospital &#124; East Suffolk & North Essex NHS Foundation Trust |publisher=Esneft.nhs.uk |date=2018-07-01 |accessdate=2018-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essexhighways.org/Transport-and-Roads/Getting-Around/Bus/Park-and-Ride/Colchester-Park-and-Ride.aspx |title=Colchester Park and Ride &#124; Essex County Council |publisher=Essexhighways.org |date=31 July 2018|accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest railway station is [[Colchester railway station|Colchester]] on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]], located 1.6 miles from the hospital.<ref name=\"esneft1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.esneft.nhs.uk/ Trust website]\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/Services/hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=13 Colchester Hospital on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.cqc.org.uk/location/RDEE4 Care Quality Commission inspection reports]\n{{Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Colchester (town)]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Essex]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colchester_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Coathill Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Coathill Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Lanarkshire]]\n| Image      = School Street (geograph 2019504).jpg\n| Caption    = Part of Coathill Hospital just visible over the wall\n| Location   = Hospital Road, [[Coatbridge]]\n| Region     = North Lanarkshire\n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = Community\n| Emergency  =\n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1861\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Scotland North Lanarkshire\n| map_caption= Shown in North Lanarkshire\n| coordinates={{Coord|55.8490|N|4.0266|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Coathill Hospital''' is a health facility in Hospital Road, [[Coatbridge]], [[North Lanarkshire]], Scotland. It is managed by [[NHS Lanarkshire]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility has its origins in the Old Monkland Poorhouse which was designed by Robert Baird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=100108|title=Robert Baird|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and opened in 1861.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/lanarkshire/|title=Coathill Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=workhouses>{{Cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Cambusnethan/|title=Cambusnethan|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> A fever hospital was built on the south part of the site in the late 19th century.<ref name=hh/> It became the Old Monkland Home Poor Law Institution in 1930.<ref name=workhouses/> There were a total of over 50 cases and suspected cases of [[typhoid fever]] in the hospital following the outbreak in Coatbridge in summer 1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1946-01-01/1946-12-31?basicsearch=typhoid&somesearch=typhoid&retrievecountrycounts=false|title=More typhoid cases likely|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=30 August 1946|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> The facility joined the [[National Health Service]] as Coathill Hospital in 1948.<ref name=hh/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Lanarkshire}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1861]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:NHS Lanarkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Coathill Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Lanarkshire]]\n| Image      = School Street (geograph 2019504).jpg\n| Caption    = Part of Coathill Hospital just visible over the wall\n| Location   = Hospital Road, [[Coatbridge]]\n| Region     = North Lanarkshire\n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = Community\n| Emergency  =\n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1861\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Scotland North Lanarkshire\n| map_caption= Shown in North Lanarkshire\n| coordinates={{Coord|55.8490|N|4.0266|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Coathill Hospital''' is a health facility in Hospital Road, [[Coatbridge]], [[North Lanarkshire]], Scotland. It is managed by [[NHS Lanarkshire]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility has its origins in the Old Monkland Poorhouse which was designed by Robert Baird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=100108|title=Robert Baird|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and opened in 1861.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/lanarkshire/|title=Coathill Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=workhouses>{{Cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Cambusnethan/|title=Cambusnethan|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> A fever hospital was built on the south part of the site in the late 19th century.<ref name=hh/> It became the Old Monkland Home Poor Law Institution in 1930.<ref name=workhouses/> There were a total of over 50 cases and suspected cases of [[typhoid fever]] in the hospital following the outbreak in Coatbridge in summer 1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/search/results/1946-01-01/1946-12-31?basicsearch=typhoid&somesearch=typhoid&retrievecountrycounts=false|title=More typhoid cases likely|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=30 August 1946|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> The facility joined the [[National Health Service]] as Coathill Hospital in 1948.<ref name=hh/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Lanarkshire}}\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1861]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:NHS Lanarkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coathill_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Clydach War Memorial Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Clydach War Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board]]\n| Image      = Clydach Hospital (geograph 2933991).jpg\n| Caption    =Clydach War Memorial Hospital\n| Logo       =\n| Location   = [[Clydach, Swansea]]\n| Region     = \n| State      = [[Wales]]\n| Country    = [[United Kingdom]]\n| HealthCare = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Type       = Community hospital\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  =\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation=\n| Beds       =\n| Founded    = 1925\n| Closed     = 2015\n| Website    =\n| Wiki-Links =\n| map_type   =Wales Swansea\n| map_caption=Shown in Swansea\n| coordinates={{coord|51.6947|-3.9013|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Clydach War Memorial Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Coffa Clydach}}) was a [[community hospital]] in [[Clydach, Swansea]], Wales. It was managed by the [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital was founded by public subscription in 1925, on land given under covenant by the owner of the local tinplate works, W.J. \"Percy\" Player. A prototype community cottage hospital specialising in front-line mining injuries from the many private mines in the Swansea Valley, it joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, but was soon overshadowed by the much larger [[Morriston Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swansea.jdi-consult.net/ldp/viewreps.php?docelemid=38804&docid=221|title=Swansea Local Development Plan|publisher=Swansea Council}}</ref> It was re-opened following a \u00a31 million refurbishment in March 2003 and continued to provide community based, clinic services until it closed in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.24housing.co.uk/news/gwalia-and-alabare-working-together-to-support-ex-servicemen-and-women/|title=Gwalia and Alabar\u00e9 working together to support ex-servicemen and women|publisher=24 Housing|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The main building was converted into apartments for ex-servicemen and women in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alabare.co.uk/news/clydach-war-memorial-hospital-given-fitting-new-lease-of-life|title=Clydach War Memorial Hospital Given Fitting New Lease Of Life|publisher=Alabare|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Swansea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Clydach War Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board]]\n| Image      = Clydach Hospital (geograph 2933991).jpg\n| Caption    =Clydach War Memorial Hospital\n| Logo       =\n| Location   = [[Clydach, Swansea]]\n| Region     = \n| State      = [[Wales]]\n| Country    = [[United Kingdom]]\n| HealthCare = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Type       = Community hospital\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  =\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation=\n| Beds       =\n| Founded    = 1925\n| Closed     = 2015\n| Website    =\n| Wiki-Links =\n| map_type   =Wales Swansea\n| map_caption=Shown in Swansea\n| coordinates={{coord|51.6947|-3.9013|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Clydach War Memorial Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Coffa Clydach}}) was a [[community hospital]] in [[Clydach, Swansea]], Wales. It was managed by the [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital was founded by public subscription in 1925, on land given under covenant by the owner of the local tinplate works, W.J. \"Percy\" Player. A prototype community cottage hospital specialising in front-line mining injuries from the many private mines in the Swansea Valley, it joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, but was soon overshadowed by the much larger [[Morriston Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swansea.jdi-consult.net/ldp/viewreps.php?docelemid=38804&docid=221|title=Swansea Local Development Plan|publisher=Swansea Council}}</ref> It was re-opened following a \u00a31 million refurbishment in March 2003 and continued to provide community based, clinic services until it closed in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.24housing.co.uk/news/gwalia-and-alabare-working-together-to-support-ex-servicemen-and-women/|title=Gwalia and Alabar\u00e9 working together to support ex-servicemen and women|publisher=24 Housing|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The main building was converted into apartments for ex-servicemen and women in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alabare.co.uk/news/clydach-war-memorial-hospital-given-fitting-new-lease-of-life|title=Clydach War Memorial Hospital Given Fitting New Lease Of Life|publisher=Alabare|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Swansea]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clydach_War_Memorial_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Clifton Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       = Clifton Hospital\n| org/group  = \n| logo       = \n| image      = Clifton Park Orthopaedic Clinic (geograph 3234147).jpg\n| caption    = The old chapel at Clifton Hospital\n| location   = [[Clifton, York]] \n| region     = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.9756|-1.1177|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= \n| beds       = \n| founded    = 1847\n| closed     = 1994\n| website    = \n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =North Yorkshire\n| map_caption=Shown in North Yorkshire\n}}\n'''Clifton Hospital''' was a mental health facility in [[Clifton, York]], England.\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which was designed by [[George Gilbert Scott]] and [[William Bonython Moffatt]] using a Corridor Plan layout, opened as the North and East Ridings Pauper Lunatic Asylum in April 1847.<ref name=county>{{cite web|url=https://www.countyasylums.co.uk/clifton-york/|title=Clifton Hospital|publisher=County Asylums|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref> The hospital was considerably extended in stages to designs developed by [[George Fowler Jones]] in the second half of the 19th century.<ref name=county/>\n\nIt became the North Riding Lunatic Asylum in 1865 and the North Riding Mental Hospital in 1920 before joining the [[National Health Service]] as Clifton Hospital in 1948.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=1565|title=Clifton Hospital, York|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the introduction of [[Care in the Community]] in the early 1980s, the hospital went into a period of decline and closed in July 1994.<ref name=county/> The main building was demolished and the site was redeveloped in part as offices for [[Norwich Union]] and in part for residential use as \"Clifton Park\" but the original chapel survives.<ref name=county/> The Clifton Park NHS Treatment Centre was erected on the site in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkstories.co.uk/york_walks-4/clifton_hospital_site.htm|title=York Walks 4|publisher=York Stories|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1847]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1847]]\n[[Category:1847 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Former psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       = Clifton Hospital\n| org/group  = \n| logo       = \n| image      = Clifton Park Orthopaedic Clinic (geograph 3234147).jpg\n| caption    = The old chapel at Clifton Hospital\n| location   = [[Clifton, York]] \n| region     = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.9756|-1.1177|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= \n| beds       = \n| founded    = 1847\n| closed     = 1994\n| website    = \n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =North Yorkshire\n| map_caption=Shown in North Yorkshire\n}}\n'''Clifton Hospital''' was a mental health facility in [[Clifton, York]], England.\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which was designed by [[George Gilbert Scott]] and [[William Bonython Moffatt]] using a Corridor Plan layout, opened as the North and East Ridings Pauper Lunatic Asylum in April 1847.<ref name=county>{{cite web|url=https://www.countyasylums.co.uk/clifton-york/|title=Clifton Hospital|publisher=County Asylums|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref> The hospital was considerably extended in stages to designs developed by [[George Fowler Jones]] in the second half of the 19th century.<ref name=county/>\n\nIt became the North Riding Lunatic Asylum in 1865 and the North Riding Mental Hospital in 1920 before joining the [[National Health Service]] as Clifton Hospital in 1948.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=1565|title=Clifton Hospital, York|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the introduction of [[Care in the Community]] in the early 1980s, the hospital went into a period of decline and closed in July 1994.<ref name=county/> The main building was demolished and the site was redeveloped in part as offices for [[Norwich Union]] and in part for residential use as \"Clifton Park\" but the original chapel survives.<ref name=county/> The Clifton Park NHS Treatment Centre was erected on the site in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkstories.co.uk/york_walks-4/clifton_hospital_site.htm|title=York Walks 4|publisher=York Stories|accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1847]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1847]]\n[[Category:1847 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Former psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifton_Hospital"}
