nt interchange]] (the centre of the city) is just 12km away.And also near Chatta '''Bakhwatar''' village.'''Bold text''' The famous anchor Javed Chaudry also lives in Shehzad town, Chakshahzad. It is also considered as a home for some important landmarks including National Agricultural Research Center, Health Services Academy (HSA),Abasyn University Islamabad Campus and COMSATS University. <ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/revealed-musharrafs-luxury-retirement-pad-900652.html Revealed: Musharraf's luxury retirement pad - Asia - World - The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Islamabad}}\n\n[[Category:Union councils of Islamabad Capital Territory]]\n[[Category:Villages in Islamabad Capital Territory]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Islamabad Capital Territory]]\n\n{{Pakistan-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ahsan Raza Alvi", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I am changes this because this area are rolled in that location)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chak_Shahzad"}
{"title_page": "Cleland Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Cleland Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Lanarkshire]]\n| Image      = Demolition at Cleland Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 699780.jpg\n| Caption    = The old Cleland Hospital being demolished\n| Location   = Auchinlea Drive, [[Cleland, North Lanarkshire|Cleland]]\n| Region     = North Lanarkshire\n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = Community\n| Emergency  =\n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1903\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Scotland North Lanarkshire\n| map_caption= Shown in North Lanarkshire\n| coordinates={{Coord|55.8028|N|3.9070|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Cleland Hospital''' is a health facility in Auchinlea Drive, [[Cleland, North Lanarkshire|Cleland]], [[North Lanarkshire]], Scotland. It is managed by [[NHS Lanarkshire]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility has its origins in the Omoa Poorhouse,{{efn|The poorhouse was named after the [[Battle of San Fernando de Omoa|Fort of San Fernando de Omoa]] which was captured by Colonel [[William Dalrymple (British Army officer)|William Dalrymple]], a local land owner, in 1779 during the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Spain and the Independence of the United States: An Intrinsic Gift|first=Thomas E|last=Ch\u00e1vez|publisher=UNM Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-8263-2794-9|ref=Chavez|oclc=149117944|pages=152\u2013153}}</ref>}} which was designed by [[Alexander Cullen (architect)|Alexander Cullen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=200389|title=Alexander Cullen|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and opened in 1903.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/lanarkshire/|title=Cleland Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Cambusnethan/|title=Cambusnethan|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> Following closure of the poorhouse in 1939, the buildings were converted for use as a military hospital during the [[World War I|Second World War]].<ref name=hh/> The new facility then joined the [[National Health Service]] as Cleland Hospital in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F276165|title=Cleland Hospital|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter services had been transferred to a modern community hospital on the east side of the site, the old hospital buildings were demolished in 2008.<ref name=hh/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Lanarkshire}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 2005]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:NHS Lanarkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Cleland Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Lanarkshire]]\n| Image      = Demolition at Cleland Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 699780.jpg\n| Caption    = The old Cleland Hospital being demolished\n| Location   = Auchinlea Drive, [[Cleland, North Lanarkshire|Cleland]]\n| Region     = North Lanarkshire\n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = Community\n| Emergency  =\n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1903\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Scotland North Lanarkshire\n| map_caption= Shown in North Lanarkshire\n| coordinates={{Coord|55.8028|N|3.9070|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Cleland Hospital''' is a health facility in Auchinlea Drive, [[Cleland, North Lanarkshire|Cleland]], [[North Lanarkshire]], Scotland. It is managed by [[NHS Lanarkshire]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility has its origins in the Omoa Poorhouse,{{efn|The poorhouse was named after the [[Battle of San Fernando de Omoa|Fort of San Fernando de Omoa]] which was captured by Colonel [[William Dalrymple (British Army officer)|William Dalrymple]], a local land owner, in 1779 during the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Spain and the Independence of the United States: An Intrinsic Gift|first=Thomas E|last=Ch\u00e1vez|publisher=UNM Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-8263-2794-9|ref=Chavez|oclc=149117944|pages=152-153}}</ref>}} which was designed by [[Alexander Cullen (architect)|Alexander Cullen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=200389|title=Alexander Cullen|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and opened in 1903.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/lanarkshire/|title=Cleland Hospital|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Cambusnethan/|title=Cambusnethan|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> Following closure of the poorhouse in 1939, the buildings were converted for use as a military hospital during the [[World War I|Second World War]].<ref name=hh/> The new facility then joined the [[National Health Service]] as Cleland Hospital in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F276165|title=Cleland Hospital|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter services had been transferred to a modern community hospital on the east side of the site, the old hospital buildings were demolished in 2008.<ref name=hh/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Lanarkshire}}\n[[Category:1903 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1903]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 2005]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:NHS Lanarkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleland_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "1988\u201389 Real Madrid CF season", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club season\n|club = Real Madrid CF\n|season = 1988\u201389\n|manager = {{flagicon|NED}} [[Leo Beenhakker]]\n|chairman = {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Ram\u00f3n Mendoza]]\n|league = [[1988\u201389 La Liga|La Liga]]\n|league result = 1\u00ba (in [[1989\u201390 European Cup]])\n|cup1 = [[1988\u201389 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]]\n|cup1 result = Champions\n|cup2 = [[1988\u201389 European Cup|European Cup]]\n|cup2 result = Semifinals \n|cup3 = [[1988 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercopa]]\n|cup3 result = Winners \n|league topscorer = {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Hugo S\u00e1nchez]] (27 goals) \n|attendance max = \n|attendance min = \n|attendance media = \n| pattern_la1=_rmcf8689 |pattern_b1=_rmcf8689 |pattern_ra1=_rmcf8689 |pattern_sh1=_rmcf8689 |pattern_so1=_RM1981\n| leftarm1=FFFFFF|body1=FFFFFF|rightarm1=FFFFFF|shorts1=FFFFFF|socks1=FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2=_rmcf8788a |pattern_b2=_rmcf8788a |pattern_ra2=_rmcf8788a |pattern_sh2=_rmcf8788a |pattern_so2=_rmcf8788a \n| leftarm2=0246d0|body2=0246d0|rightarm2=0246d0|shorts2=0246d0|socks2=0246d0\n|prevseason = [[1987\u201388 Real Madrid CF season|1987\u201388]]\n|nextseason = [[1989\u201390 Real Madrid CF season|1989\u201390]]\n}}\n\nThe 1988\u201389 season is Real Madrid Club de F\u00fatbol's 87th season in existence and the club's 58th consecutive season in the top flight of Spanish football.\n\n== Season ==\nReal Madrid finished the season as champions for the fourth season running, 5 points ahead of the runners-up this time being FC Barcelona. This was its 24th title in history.\n\n== Squad ==\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/teams/real-madrid/1989/2/ |title=Real Madrid \u00bb Squad 1988/1989 |publisher=worldfootball.net |date= |accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=ESP|name=[[Agust\u00edn (footballer)|Agust\u00edn Rodr\u00edguez]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=ESP|name=[[Francisco Buyo]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=|n